Abstract

This data report (and associated datasets) documents the acquisition and preparation of National Park Service (NPS) custom areas of analysis (AOAs) for use within the Inventory and Monitoring Program (I&M). AOA datasets were updated through September 30, 2018 and supersede all previous releases/versions.

The Inventory and Monitoring Division (IMD), under the I&M Program, works with a select subset of the more than 400 park units of the National Park System; NPS parks that are part of the I&M Program are included in this subset. Landscape dynamics, weather, and stream hydrology measures are monitored using methods outlined in the National Park Environmental Settings Monitoring Protocol (DeVivo et.al 2018), which includes areas inside and near parks with significant natural resources. Annually, AOAs are updated or created based on custom requests. AOA datasets documented in this report and may not include all NPS units, or other NPS areas. These AOAs are not official boundaries and are not intended for use outside NPS Inventory and Monitoring..

1 Background and Summary

The status and condition of park resources is affected by interconnected system drivers at regional to global scales surrounding parks. Landscape dynamics provide an important context for understanding patterns and changes in resources monitored at parks. The National Park Environmental Settings Monitoring Protocol produces nationally-standardized status and trend information related to Landscape Dynamics, Climate, and Surface Water Dynamics metrics (DeVivo et al. 2018).

Annually, IMD calculates protocol metrics for areas of analysis (AOAs). AOAs are defined geographic extents of interest. Custom AOAs include any area of interest to a park or network. Only AOAs submitted by I&M Program parks or networks are included in the custom AOA dataset. Not all NPS units are represented in the custom AOA dataset.

2 Methods

The creation of custom AOAs takes place annually. Custom AOAs are derived from and utilize custom polygons submitted by parks or networks. Custom AOAs (NPS IMD 2018) are used in support of the National Park Environmental Settings Monitoring Protocol (DeVivo et al. 2018). This report documents the incorporation of new and/or updated custom AOAs submitted by a park or network (Figure 1) from September 30, 2017 through September 30, 2018 (NPS IMD 2018b). In that time period, two custom AOAs were submitted for inclusion in the dataset (see Tables 1 and 7 below).

Figure 1. General process flow for custom landscape dynamics AOAs. Orange items indicate datasets generated with this report. Dash-outlined items may or may not be generated annually; there may or may not be custom AOAs submitted each year.

2.1.2 Previous Custom AOA Dataset

Unless otherwise notified by the respective park or network, all submitted custom AOAs will be used indefinitely (NPS IMD 2018a), and any new and/or updated submissions are merged with the preceding dataset.

2.2 Create Custom AOAs

New and/or updated network-submitted polygons were combined into one collective dataset and additional attribute fields and domains managed by IMD staff were added. See Appendix C for the required script to create the published custom AOA output.

2.2.1 Documenting Change in Custom AOAs

The attribute “change reason from preceding version” for custom AOAs indicates why a custom AOA boundary change occurred (Tables 2 and 3). After creating custom AOAs, all new and/or changed custom AOAs were identified based on the following criteria: (1) a previously unused custom AOA was identified and incorporated into the dataset; (2) a previously used custom AOA was changed by the Network and the updated version supersedes the preceding version; (3) a previously used custom AOA is no longer in use and was removed (inactivated) from the dataset; (4) a previously used custom AOA does not meet any of the above criteria, there was no change. See Appendix B for a full list of all added, changed, or removed custom AOAs (Table 7).

Table 2. Criteria for identifying changes in custom AOAs and the associated change reason from preceding version label and definition.

Criteria Change Reason from Preceding Version Label Change Reason from Preceding Version Definition
Custom AOA was previously not included in the custom AOA dataset; it was added for use. Added feature Addition of previously unused feature
Custom AOA has been changed by the Network; the updated version supersedes the preceding version Update Update to dynamically edited data where there are no released versions
Custom AOA is no longer included in the custom AOA dataset, it was removed from use. Removed feature Removal of feature used in preceding version
Custom AOA does not meet other criteria, the custom AOA has not changed from preceding version No change No change

Change reason applies only to the current version of custom AOAs (NPS IMD 2018b) when compared to the preceding version of custom AOAs (NPS IMD 2017).

  1. Landscape Dynamics Custom AOAs (IMD_BND_ESProtocol_Custom_AOA.gdb). 4 Data Quality Evaluation

Spatial and attribute quality is not quantified in the source data (NPS IMD 2018b) used to produce the landscape dynamics custom AOAs output.

5 Usage Notes

The AOA datasets are intended and suitable for use in the collection, analysis, and reporting of metric statistics for the National Park Environmental Setting Monitoring Protocol, or for use in visualization products like web map applications. AOAs may be used in other work by the NPS I&M Program, or Inventory and Monitoring Division, including inventories. These AOAs are not official boundaries and are not intended for use outside NPS Inventory and Monitoring.

9 Appendix C. Python Code to Create Landscape Dynamics Custom AOAs

The following script will convert all custom AOAs for use. This script is only applicable to the datasets cited in this report.

import os, time

“IMD_BND_ESProtocol_Custom_AOA.gdb”

["IMD_BND_ESProtocol_Custom_albers_py","IMD_BND_ESProtocol_Custom_wgs_py"]

DOM_NETREG = "DOM_NETWORKS_REGIONS_NPSIMD2019"

ConusSpatialRef = arcpy.SpatialReference(102039)

The National Park Service, Natural Resource Stewardship and Science office in Fort Collins, Colorado, publishes a range of reports that address natural resource topics. These reports are of interest and applicability to a broad audience in the National Park Service and others in natural resource management, including scientists, conservation and environmental constituencies, and the public.

The Natural Resource Data Series is intended for the timely release of basic data sets and data summaries. Care has been taken to assure accuracy of raw data values, but a thorough analysis and interpretation of the data has not been completed. Consequently, the initial analyses of data in this report are provisional and subject to change.

All manuscripts in the series receive the appropriate level of peer review to ensure that the information is scientifically credible, technically accurate, appropriately written for the intended audience, and designed and published in a professional manner.

The creation of data sets documented in this report followed peer reviewed methods described or referenced herein. Resultant data sets were reviewed to ensure accuracy, completeness, and consistency with documented data quality standards, as well as for usability and reproducibility.

Views, statements, findings, conclusions, recommendations, and data in this report do not necessarily reflect views and policies of the National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior. Mention of trade names or commercial products does not constitute endorsement or recommendation for use by the U.S. Government.

This report is available in digital format from the National Park Service Data Store. To receive this report in a format that is optimized to be accessible using screen readers for the visually or cognitively impaired, please email irma@nps.gov.
